  "11": {
    "Walter Brueggemann, Warren Carter": "Sentence: I will tear the kingdom from you. (11:11)\nThis theological perspective dares to assert that the rise and fall of\npower and the turn of public destiny depends singularly upon\nTorah obedience. In what follows this clear, simple theological\nEchoes of Davidic Judgment\nThe image of \u201ctearing\u201d as a way of speaking about\nthe abrupt and violent transfer of power from one leader to\nanother is twice stated (11:11, 31). Whereas this son of\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` is the loser in this subversive transaction, the same\nrhetoric is earlier employed on David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s behalf:\nThe LORD has torn the kingdom of Israel from you this\nvery day, and has given it to a neighbor of yours, who is\n[v_1Sa_15_28] better than you. (1 Sam 15:28)\nThe LORD has torn the kingdom out of your hand, and\n[v_1Sa_28_17] given it to your neighbor, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`. (1 Sam 28:17; see 1\nSam 13:14)\nWhat the family of David `[char_David_Rut_4]` receives as a gift from Yahweh (in\nthe time of Saul) is taken from them by the same action of\nYahweh. The parallel rhetoric is surely deliberate. The power-\nful in Israel are always again relearning respect for the\noverriding claim of Yahweh:\n\u2026until you have learned that the Most High has sover-\neignty over the kingdom of mortals, and gives it to\n[v_Dan_4_25] whom he will. (Dan 4:25)\nconviction is clearly only worked out in the vagaries of the public\nprocess. The statement itself, however, concedes nothing to these\ncomplications. Israel is now on notice that everything depends\nupon Torah, a truth remote from the horizon of the great regime of\nSolomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`.\nThe verdict of\nv. 11 effectively ends the regime of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` from\na theological perspective. But of course such theological judgments,\nno matter how passionately entertained, cannot override the reality\nthat takes place on the ground. For that reason, vv. 12-13 must add\ntwo important qualifications to the devastating announcement.\nFirst, the kingdom did not end in Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`\u2019s lifetime, but persists",
    "John Trapp": "Wherefore the Lord said unto Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`. ] He said it, and he did: though Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` repented, yet since the decree was come forth, it was accomplished. Repentance may come too late in respect of temporal judgments. I will surely rend the kingdom. ] God loves to retaliate. Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had let go the sincere service of God by sharing himself between him and idols: his servant therefore shall share the kingdom with his son, and bear away the better half from him.\nVer.\n11. Wherefore the Lord said unto Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`.] He said it, and he did: though Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` repented, yet since the decree was come forth, it was accomplished. Repentance may come too late in respect of temporal judgments. I will surely rend the kingdom.] God loves to retaliate. Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had let go the sincere service of God by sharing himself between him and idols: his servant therefore shall share the kingdom with his son, and bear away the better half from him.\nVer."
  },
  "12": {
    "Walter Brueggemann, Warren Carter": "in its Solomonic form into the reign of his son Rehoboam (11:12).\nSecond, the loss of the kingdom did not entail the loss of\nJerusalem, Judah, or Benjamin that the Davidic house retained for\na very long time. Thus the severe judgment is tempered by lived\nreality. The mitigating grace is expressed theologically in a double\n\u201cfor the sake of,\u201d for David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, for Jerusalem, Yahweh\u2019s two great loves\n11:12\n187, 374",
    "John Trapp": "Out of the hand of thy son, ] i.e., Rehoboam, the only son that Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had by so many wives and concubines, quod prodigii instar est, saith one, which may well seem a wonder. See #Ps 127:1 Ho 4:10 { See Trapp on title of \"Ps 127:1\" }\nVer.\n12. Out of the hand of thy son, ] i.e., Rehoboam, the only son that Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` had by so many wives and concubines, quod prodigii [v_Psa_127_1] instar est, saith one, which may well seem a wonder. See #Ps 127:1 [v_Hos_4_10] Ho 4:10 {See Trapp on title of \"Ps 127:1\"}\nVer.\n12. The Lord is gracious and full of compassion: he quickly repenteth him of the evil, and leaveth a blessing behind him. One tribe.] Benjamin is reckoned as part of Judah, because within [v_Jos_19_1] him. {#Jos 19:1,9} For David `[char_David_Rut_4]` my servant\u2019s sake.] Five times in this chapter is David `[char_David_Rut_4]` honoured with this title, and therein God\u2019s dear respects unto him expressed: but all of mere mercy. How this message wrought upon Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` is uncertain. Some hold that hereupon he repented; others judge otherwise, and that (1.) Because he replied nothing; (2.) Because that after this he sought to slay Jeroboam, to prevent the rending away of his kingdom threatened, as Saul did to slay David `[char_David_Rut_4]`.\nVer."
  },
  "22": {
    "Walter Brueggemann, Warren Carter": "the regime of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` has one\nsmoldering antagonist held in check by the persuasiveness of\nPharaoh.\nWe are told even less about the second \u201cadversary,\u201d Rezon\n(11:23-25). He is a fugitive from the government of Zobah, and he\neventually becomes king of Syria (Aram). Though he takes no\naction against Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`, the narrative refers to the \u201cslaughter by\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]`,\u201d perhaps appealing to the action reported in\nv.",
    "John Trapp": "Howbeit let me go in any wise. ] Heb., No, but in sending send me away. Fugiamus et nos ad clarissimarn patriam: hasten we also to heaven, though the world would detain us longer here by her blandishments and largesses, Rivers run to the sea, whence they came; the dove returneth to the ark; &amp;c. Nature hath ingrafted in every creature to love the place where it took birth and beginning.\nVer.\n22. Howbeit let me go in any wise.] Heb., No, but in sending send me away. Fugiamus et nos ad clarissimarn patriam: hasten we also to heaven, though the world would detain us longer here by her blandishments and largesses, Rivers run to the sea, whence they came; the dove returneth to the ark; &c. Nature hath ingrafted in every creature to love the place where it took birth and beginning.\nVer."
  },
